## Implementation Details

### Framework-Specific Configuration
According to the latest Vercel Speed Insights documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), for React applications the correct approach is:

```typescript
import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/react';

export default function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      {/* content */}
      <SpeedInsights />
    </div>
  );
}
```

This project follows this exact pattern, confirming proper implementation.

### Additional Components
The project also has Vercel Analytics installed (`@vercel/analytics` v2.0.1), which is complementary to Speed Insights and provides additional analytics capabilities.

## Next Steps for Monitoring

To start seeing Speed Insights data:

1. **Enable Speed Insights on Vercel Dashboard**:
   - Navigate to your Vercel project dashboard
   - Go to the Speed Insights section in the sidebar
   - Click "Enable" to activate the feature
   - This will create routes at `/_vercel/speed-insights/*` on next deployment

2. **Deploy to Vercel**:
   - The code is already configured correctly
   - Deploy using `vercel deploy` or via Git integration
   - Speed Insights will automatically start collecting data

3. **Monitor Core Web Vitals**:
   - After deployment and user visits, access the Speed Insights dashboard
   - View metrics for:
     - Largest Contentful Paint (LCP)
     - First Input Delay (FID)
     - Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS)
     - First Contentful Paint (FCP)
     - Time to First Byte (TTFB)
     - Interaction to Next Paint (INP)

